00:05:30.680 --> 00:05:33.870
and letting you know how
special and wonderful they are.

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:37.380
This year we have a number of books
that explore the hidden histories

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:42.330 position:56%
of Latin America and their
influence here in the United States.

00:05:42.330 --> 00:05:44.510
Once again, Margarita Engle brings

00:05:44.510 --> 00:05:48.450
to life the little-known
historical events from Cuba

00:05:48.450 --> 00:05:53.180
in her poetic novel, Lion Island,
about Chinese indentured servants

00:05:53.180 --> 00:05:57.490
and others who escape
persecution to find refuge in Cuba

00:05:57.490 --> 00:05:59.560
in the late 19th century.

00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:01.830
They become warriors of words,

00:06:01.830 --> 00:06:05.750
proving that violence is not
the only way to gain liberty.

00:06:05.750 --> 00:06:08.880
The Princess and the
Warrior is another great work

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:11.770
by previous Americas
Award Winner and author

00:06:11.770 --> 00:06:14.850
and illustrator, Duncan Tonatiuh.

00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:19.090
The author draws from vibrant
cultural history and symbolism

00:06:19.090 --> 00:06:24.250
from the Azteca, to retell a
romantic legend of two volcanoes,

00:06:24.250 --> 00:06:28.280
evoking storytellers
from times long past.

00:06:28.280 --> 00:06:32.290
Lowriders to the Center of the
Earth, written by Kathy Camper

00:06:32.290 --> 00:06:37.830 position:56%
and illustrated by Raul, III,
features Lupe, Elirio, and El Chavo,

00:06:37.830 --> 00:06:40.540
who take a rollicking
ride to the underworld

00:06:40.540 --> 00:06:42.890
as they search for their lost cat.

00:06:42.890 --> 00:06:47.640
With puns, mariachi lyrics,
and lingo of the lowriders,

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:52.400
this is an unforgettable journey
to the realm of the Aztec past.

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:55.240
Another hidden history
is found in the School

00:06:55.240 --> 00:07:01.310 position:56%
That the Aztec Eagles Built, written
by Dorinda Makanaonalani Nicholson.

00:07:01.310 --> 00:07:06.370
It's the inspirational World
War II story of Angel Bocanegra,

00:07:06.370 --> 00:07:09.910
a dedicated teacher from
Mexico who volunteers

00:07:09.910 --> 00:07:12.860
for the fighting pilots,
the Aztec Eagles.

00:07:12.860 --> 00:07:16.480
His promise to return to his
community and build a school are

00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:21.200
as inspirational as
the military missions.

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:25.830
Shame the Stars, by Guadalupe
Garcia McCall is a Romeo

00:07:25.830 --> 00:07:29.980
and Juliet story set against the
backdrop of the border troubles

00:07:29.980 --> 00:07:35.950
of 1915 between native Tejanos
and the white Texas Rangers.

00:07:35.950 --> 00:07:39.690
With authentic newspaper
clippings and original poetry,

00:07:39.690 --> 00:07:45.590
this is another book that shows the
power of speech to right injustice.

00:07:45.590 --> 00:07:49.860
Juana and Lucas, written by Juana
Medina, is a more whimsical book.

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:53.630
An illustrated journey through
Bogota, Colombia, through the eyes

00:07:53.630 --> 00:07:58.030
of quirky Juana and her
furry amigo, her dog Lucas.

00:07:58.030 --> 00:08:00.490
Juana, too, learns
the power of words

00:08:00.490 --> 00:08:05.110
and how languages open
doorways to other cultures.

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:09.390 position:56%
Another common theme running through
these books is the power of art

00:08:09.390 --> 00:08:12.860
and how it can represent the
history of people, which is found

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:16.950
in Rainbow Weaver, written
by Linda Elovitz Marshall

00:08:16.950 --> 00:08:19.820
and illustrated by Elisa Chavarri.

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:25.040
With her Mayan weavings that are
made from repurposed plastic bags,

00:08:25.040 --> 00:08:29.470
young Ixchel is able to pay for
her own books and her schooling,

00:08:29.470 --> 00:08:34.060
which emphasizes Ixchel's
agency and her ingenuity.

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:38.980
In Radiant Child, author Javaka
Steptoe reveals the biography

00:08:38.980 --> 00:08:41.870
of street artist Jean-Michel
Basquiat,

00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:45.630
while showcasing his developing
work from childhood on,

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:49.360
making it accessible to
even the youngest reader.

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:52.850
Margarito's Forest, written
by Andy Carter and illustrated

00:08:52.850 --> 00:08:56.890
by Allison Havens, tells us
the story of Don Margarito

00:08:56.890 --> 00:09:01.430 position:56%
and his lifelong commitment to
plant trees in his native Guatemala.

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:04.350
This trilingual book,
with English, Spanish,

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:09.250 position:56%
and captions in the indigenous local
Mayan language, combines artwork

00:09:09.250 --> 00:09:12.190
of a professional illustrator
and the children

00:09:12.190 --> 00:09:14.960
of Don Margarito's village.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:18.450
Another thing we see in our
committed titles is the power

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:21.830
of emotion and standing
up for yourself.

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:25.170
In the Memory of Light,
written by Francisco Stork,

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:29.550
main character Vicki learns to
trust in others, trust in herself,

00:09:29.550 --> 00:09:33.670
and stand up for herself to her
family, who seem to only care

00:09:33.670 --> 00:09:39.400 position:56%
about career, success, and the
monetary side of the American dream.

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:42.370
Inspired by the author's
own experiences,

00:09:42.370 --> 00:09:46.050
this young adult novel provides
a powerful message of acceptance

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:49.980
and empowerment for anyone
struggling with depression.

00:09:49.980 --> 00:09:56.510 position:56%
In Meg Medina's Burn Baby Burn, Nora
Lopez also faces problems at home

00:09:56.510 --> 00:10:01.740
and violence in the streets of
summertime 1977 New York City,

00:10:01.740 --> 00:10:06.520
when disco was king, temperatures
were hot, and frighteningly,

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:08.320
son of Sam was on the loose.

00:10:08.320 --> 00:10:12.810
This novel confronts
problems of first

00:10:12.810 --> 00:10:16.520
and second generation Cuban
immigrants, families members

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:20.440
who love each other but who do not
see the world from the same lens.

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:25.820
And finally, the theme of
immigration is the last theme

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:29.540
of these commended titles, next
seen in the children's book,

00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:35.020 position:56%
Somos como las nubes, We are Like
the Clouds, written by Jorge Argueta

00:10:35.020 --> 00:10:37.850
and illustrated by Alphonso Verano.

00:10:37.850 --> 00:10:43.640
The dreamy poetry and images in
this book contrasts beautifully

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:46.370
with the harsh realities
of migration

00:10:46.370 --> 00:10:49.250
from Central America to the north.

00:10:49.250 --> 00:10:54.450
The migrants become a family
of stars and move miraculously

00:10:54.450 --> 00:10:58.290
across the miles like the
clouds, como las nubes.

00:10:58.290 --> 00:11:05.400 position:56%
And finally, we have Mama the
Alien, written by Rene Colato Lainez

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:08.890
and illustrated by Laura Lacamara.

00:11:08.890 --> 00:11:12.480
When Sophia looks at her
mother's old drivers license,

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:15.550
she discovers that her
mother is an alien.

00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:18.850 position:56%
And she first imagines that her
mother must come from another planet

00:11:18.850 --> 00:11:21.410
and that she's got alien friends

00:11:21.410 --> 00:11:24.810
who will soon visit
her in a flying saucer.

00:11:24.810 --> 00:11:28.920
This clever book compares or
clarifies the important topic

00:11:28.920 --> 00:11:32.640
of immigration and the process
of becoming a US citizen.

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:37.410
In the author's note she
remarks, I want readers to know

00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:41.320
that immigrants may be referred
to as aliens, but this only means

00:11:41.320 --> 00:11:43.190 position:56%
